  <section id="ai-and-clarity" class="content-section">
    <h2>On AI and This Site</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">The same philosophy applies to how this site was written.</p>
    <div class="origin-story">
      <p>I write in streams of consciousness. What comes out is tangled, recursive, full of half-finished thoughts that loop back on themselves. It's accurate. It's complete. It's also exhausting to read.</p>
      <p>For years, the solution was to agonize &mdash; wordsmith the sentence, spend twenty minutes sounding &ldquo;professional,&rdquo; which usually meant sounding like everyone else: fine, forgettable, friction-filled to produce.</p>
      <p>I brain-dump now, hand it to an AI, and review what comes back. The ideas are mine. The AI's job is to make it readable &mdash; to do what a good editor does, which is get out of the way of the meaning.</p>
      <p>This isn't laziness. It's the same philosophy I apply to code.</p>
      <p>Good code is self-documenting. When I inherit a codebase that requires a novel of inline comments to navigate, that's a smell &mdash; the code is failing to communicate. Professional writing has the same failure mode. The friction of converting thought to readable prose was never adding value to the thinking itself.</p>
      <p><em>&ldquo;AI wrote it&rdquo;</em> is a mischaracterization. <em>AI clarified it.</em></p>
      <p>The thinking, the investigation, the conclusions &mdash; those are mine. What I'm outsourcing is the translation friction. My prime directive is clarity. If an AI can take a tangled first draft and make it immediately readable &mdash; and I can review it, own it, and stand behind every word &mdash; the communication succeeded.</p>
      <p>The question isn't &ldquo;did AI touch this.&rdquo;</p>
      <p><strong>The question is: does the reader understand what I meant to say?</strong></p>
      <p class="methodology-note">Much of this site was built with AI assistance &mdash; content, code, and design. The thinking behind it is mine. The clarity is the point. That's <em>Provider of Clarity</em> applied to its own medium.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
